ce:section.ce:para:
Based on the excellent PL properties of the Si-CQDs and BH can prominently quench the emission of the Si-CQDs, the Si-CQDs were employed to determine BH. As shown in Fig. 4
                        a, the emission intensity of the Si-CQDs at 440 nm decreases gradually as the concentration increase of the BH. Furthermore, there is a good linear relationship between BH concentrations and the emission intensity of the Si-CQDs. The linear equation can be fitted as ΔF = 55.16c + 135.64 (BH, μmol/L) over the range from 0.5 to 30 μmol/L with a correlation coefficient (R2) of 0.9945 and a LOD of 50 nmol/L (Fig. 4b). Compared with previous methods (Table 1
                        ), the LOD of the proposed assay has obvious advantages. This method also has the superiorities of simplicity and low cost, and has great potential in practical application. Similarly, the up-conversion fluorescence also can be quenched by BH. As shown in Fig. 4c, the up-conversion fluorescence intensities decreased gradually with the increase of BH concentrations, and the quenching intensities are related to the BH concentrations in a range of 0-25 μmol/L with the linear equation is ΔF = 1.445c + 0.928, the R2 is 0.9978. All results show that the Si-CQDs have a sensitive response to BH, and their up- and down-conversion fluorescence can be utilized to realize dual-mode recognition of BH.
